article.description: Courtney Ward scored 18 points and Tanae Davis-Cain had 16 as Florida State held off a second-half rally by Virginia and won 80-75. It was the Seminoles' eighth consecutive victory.
article.headline: Streaking Seminoles hold off late Cavaliers' rally
article.linkText: Florida State holds off UVa for 8th straight win
article.story:
CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. -- A run to end the first half that was capped by a 3-point fling that banked in at the buzzer gave Florida State a big momentum shift at Virginia.

The Seminoles (No. 23 ESPN/USA Today, No. 22 AP) didn't waste it, pulling away from and then holding off a furious rally by the Cavaliers (No. 14 ESPN/USA Today, No. 16 AP) to hang on, 80-75 on Friday night.

"It was just like we drew it up," Jacinta Monroe said of Courtney Ward's heave from the top of the key to end the first half, bursting into laughter with Ward and coach Sue Semrau.

But laughter is becoming common for the Seminoles (17-4, 5-0 Atlantic Coast Conference). They are off to their best start in ACC history and showed what they can do against a good team on the road, making them eager for upcoming visits from Duke (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today, No. 4 AP) and Maryland (No. 13 ESPN/USA Today, No. 12 AP).

In the second half, "we went out and really played team basketball," said Ward, who led the Seminoles with 18 points before fouling out. Tanae Davis-Cain had 16 before she also fouled out, and Alysha Harvin scored 14. Ward and Davis-Cain each made four 3-pointers.

Monroe, Florida State's top scorer entering the game, did her part, too, making both ends of a one-and-one with 20.5 seconds left after Virginia had closed to within 74-73.

The team practices pressure free throw shooting regularly in practice, Monroe said, so "I just step up to the line and just shoot" when sent to the line in the clutch, she said.

Virginia (15-4, 2-2) got within one numerous times in the closing minutes but never tied it as the Seminoles always found an answer. Mara Freshour added two free throws with 9.9 seconds to play, after Monica Wright's basket drew Virginia to 76-75 with 11.3 seconds left.

"It was intense, but we stayed focused," Monroe said.

Florida State used a 26-9 run spanning the halves to seemingly take control. The Seminoles led by 13 twice after halftime, but Virginia fought back each time with help from its crowd.

Trailing 67-54 after an 8-0 run by Florida State, the Cavaliers went on a 12-0 run helped by a technical foul against Florida State's Cierra Bravard with 5:05 left. Lyndra Littles made both technical shots, and Wright added a pair of free throws, pulling Virginia within 67-66.

The game went back and forth thereafter with Monroe getting an easy putback off a missed free throw, Davis-Cain following two free throws by Wright with a driving basket and Ward following a basket by Aisha Mohammed in the lane with her final 3-pointer to make it 74-70.

When Wright hit twice more from the line to pull Virginia within two, two misses by Harvin had the crowd imploring the Cavaliers to finally grab the lead, but freshman Chelsea Shine made only the second of two free throws with one minute left and Monroe's two were critical.

Virginia had its defense to blame, 32nd-year coach Debbie Ryan said.

"They got the lead and then our defensive intensity at those points was not good enough to win the game," Ryan said. "We had to have a stop and we couldn't get one."

Wright led Virginia with 24 points but shot just 6-for-19 and missed a 3-point try in the final seconds that would have tied it at 78. Littles added 21 points and Mohammed had 15.

"A game like this is hard to digest," Littles said. "There's no way you fight that hard and lose the game. It's very disappointing and discouraging."
